IN these days, when, like everything else, shipping has 
made such rapid strides that journeys which formerly were 
looked upon with awe, and undertaken only in extreme 
necessity, are now made with positive indifference, we are 
too apt to look upon the sea as a liquid railway ; to think 
that, with the piracy and the lubberly vessels that sailed 
the main in the olden days, the romance of ocean has 

